The '''red-shouldered vanga''' ('''''Calicalicus rufocarpalis''''') is a member of the [[vanga]] family [[endemism|endemic]] to south-west [[Madagascar]].<ref name="iucn status 13 November 2021" />

This species is notable for being the last species viewed by internationally renowned bird watcher [[Phoebe Snetsinger]] before her 1999 death in Madagascar.<ref>{{cite book |title=Zen Birding |page=16 |first1=David M. |last1=White |first2=Susan M. |last2=Guyette |publisher=O Books |year=2010 |location=Ropley, Hampshire |isbn=978-1-84694-389-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RDLHoB6mNmEC&q=%22phoebe+snetsinger%22+%22red-shouldered+vanga%22&pg=PA16}}</ref>

== Description ==
Like many of the vangas, this species is [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]]; the male is the more colorful of the two.  He has a pale gray crown, nape and mantle, with white on the ear coverts and forehead.  Other than a black bib, which extends from the beak partway down the breast and up the sides of his neck, his underparts are principally whitish, tinged with pink on the breast and flanks.  His [[flight feather]]s are brown, his [[wing covert]]s are brick-red, and his tail is a pale brick-red. His beak is black, his [[Iris (anatomy)|irides]] are yellow, and his legs and feet are pinkish-gray.<ref name="Morris">{{cite book |last1=Morris |first1=Pete |first2=Frank |last2=Hawkins |title=Birds of Madagascar: A Photographic Guide |year=1998 |publisher=Pica Press |location=Mountfield, UK |isbn=1-873403-45-3 |pages=242–243}}</ref>

== Conservation and threats ==
The species has been rated as [[Vulnerable species|Vulnerable]] by the [[IUCN]], based on its low population numbers and very small range.<ref name="iucn status 13 November 2021" />

